Process:
1) Fetch the original issue (description AND all comments):
   `gh issue view __INUM__ --json title,body,comments`
   Read every comment. Build a checklist of what the issue requires: acceptance criteria, reproduction steps, expected behavior, and any clarifications from comments.
2) Inspect PR: `gh pr view __PR__ --json files,commits,body,number,baseRefName,headRefName,url`
3) MANDATORY ISSUE RESOLUTION CHECK - request_changes if ANY of these fail:
   - Every requirement from the issue description is addressed by the PR
   - Every clarification or additional requirement from issue comments is addressed
   - The fix matches the expected behavior described in the issue
   - Edge cases or reproduction steps mentioned in comments are covered
   - Nothing was added that the issue did not ask for (no scope creep)
   - PR verification includes requirement-by-requirement evidence (tests/commands/output excerpts/artifact paths) proving each issue requirement is resolved
   If ANYTHING is missing, incomplete, deviates from what the issue requested, or lacks concrete evidence of full resolution: STOP, do NOT fix it yourself, set FINAL_REVIEW_STATUS to request_changes with a specific list of what is missing or wrong relative to the issue requirements, and hand the PR back to the implementer.
4) Review code for correctness, compliance, and quality. Do NOT run tests or build - CI handles that; baseline is always green per repo policy.
5) MANDATORY COMPLIANCE CHECK: Validate against project CLAUDE.md/AGENTS.md AND user CLAUDE.md/AGENTS.md STRICTLY
6) Classify findings:
   - BLOCKING: breaks tests, build, correctness, violates hard limits (module >1000 lines, function >100 lines), violates ANY CLAUDE.md/AGENTS.md rule, OR fails to resolve any issue requirement
   - DEFER: style polish, minor refactors, documentation improvements, soft limit suggestions
7) Fix blocking code issues (NOT missing-requirement issues): stage specific files, commit, push. Only if you made changes, run tests and build locally to verify.
8) For deferred items: open focused GitHub issues (one per concern) with label "polish". Keep scope narrow to avoid feature creep.
9) Decide review status based on blocking issues AND issue resolution completeness.

